%div#professional-tab.container.mt-3
  %div
    %p.fw-bold
      Professional Biography...
      %button.btn.btn-outline-info.btn-sm{ "style": "--bs-btn-padding-y: .05rem;", "data-bs-toggle": "collapse", "href": "#about-intro-text", "role": "button", "aria-expanded": "false", "aria-controls": "about-intro-text" }
        + -

  %div
    %div.collapse#about-intro-text
      %div.card.card-body.bg-light.border-light.text-justify.mb-3
        %p
          I was a
          = link_to "Rails", "http://rubyonrails.org/", target: "_blank"
          developer from 2009 to 2019, and I’ve been working with the
          = link_to "Ruby", "https://www.ruby-lang.org/en/", target: "_blank"
          language since 2005.
        %p
          Prior to that, I worked for 27 years in the semiconductor industry at
          = link_to "Ford Microelectronics",
            "https://search.brave.com/search?q=ford+microelectronics",
            target: "_blank"
          &#44;
          = link_to "Cypress Semiconductor", "http://www.cypress.com/", target: "_blank"
          (acquired by Infineon), and
          = link_to "IBM", "https://www.ibm.com/us-en/", target: "_blank"
          &#46; I was a
          = link_to "DevOps", "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DevOps", target: "_blank"
          before the buzzword was invented: doing a combination of software development and system administration, as well as acting as the local SME for the
          = link_to "Electronic Design Automation Tools", "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronic_design_automation", target: "_blank"
          essential for the creation of
          = link_to "VLSI", "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Very-large-scale_integration", target: "_blank"
          components.
        %p
          My Ford career in the 1980s was great fun. A
          = link_to "Motor City", "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Detroit", target: "_blank"
          exile working for a car company in Colorado - it doesn’t get any better than that. We were designing first generation automotive electronics during the week and running
          = link_to "Mustangs", "https://www.cargurus.com/Cars/1988-Ford-Mustang-Pictures-c3705#entity=t30287&pictureId=35729363", target: "_blank"
          and
          = link_to "T-birds", "https://www.cargurus.com/Cars/1987-Ford-Thunderbird-Pictures-c4641#entity=t33414&pictureId=19867112", target: "_blank"
          in
          = link_to "SCCA", "https://www.scca.com/", target: "_blank"
          Solo II competition on the weekends. Motor Head Nirvana.
        %div.text-center
          %img.img-fluid{"src": "/images/about/scca.webp", "alt": "scca"}
          %p.figure-caption
            1989 Ford Thunderbird, supercharged, intercooled 210 HP

        %p
          But all things come to an end, and when I ran out of interesting things to do at Ford I jumped ship to a VLSI design startup. That company went under the following year, but the design team was picked up by
          Cypress, and I worked 14 years at the Colorado Springs Design Center where we designed static RAMs, generating over $1.5 billion in revenue for the company.
        %div.text-center
          %img.img-fluid{"src": "/images/about/Cypress_72MbitQDRII_SRAM.webp", "alt": "chip"}
          %p.figure-caption
            The Cypress Colorado Springs Design Center specializes in SRAM design

        %p
          The
          = link_to "Dot Com", "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dot-com_bubble", target: "_blank"
          crash of 2000 seriously affected the semiconductor industry, and after dodging more layoffs than I care to remember, my number came up in 2005, and that was the end of the road with Cypress.
        %p
          The crew that was cut from Cypress represented a huge amount of VLSI expertise, and we persuaded IBM to let us set up a new VLSI design center in Colorado Springs. Yet another semiconductor market pullback ultimately killed that idea, and as an unwilling participant in the
          = link_to "IBM 2009 layoffs", "http://money.cnn.com/2009/02/05/news/companies/ibm_jobs/", target: "_blank"
          &#44; I decided it was long past time to stop chasing electrons. Fortunately, I had been hacking on Rails web sites and doing Ruby programming for awhile, so the transition to Rails Web Developer was a viable ten year “second career” choice, which included seven years working at Comcast. In 2019, after 40+ years of contributing to the advance of technology, I decided it was time to hang up my spurs and complete the transition to retirement. Cheers!
        %img.img-thumbnail{"src": "/images/cwl2a-cartoon.webp",
          "style": "width: 121px; height: 80px;",
          "alt": "gravatar"}
        %p
          Click
          = link_to "here", "/files/cwl-resume.pdf", target: "_blank"
          for my major career highlights (in PDF formt).

